From David Lewis Subject Frequently Asked Questions FAQ Archive name x faq Last modified Subject How do I make a screendump or print my application The xwd client in the distributions can be used to select a window or the It produces an XWD format file of the image of that The file can be post processed into something useful or printed with the xpr client and your local printing You can use this command csh sleep xwd root and then spend seconds or so setting up your screen the entire current display will be saved into the file Note that xwd also has an undocumented before id flag for specifying the window id on the command There are also unofficial patches on export to xwd for specifying the delay and the portion of the screen to Two publicly available programs which allow interactive definition of arbitrary portions of the display and built in delays are asnap and There are several versions of xgrabsc version available on export is the most xsnap includes some asnap features and supersedes it it also renders XPM output version unknown It is available on export or see xsnap A screen dump and merge edit program combining features of xwd and xpr is available from as Information xprint by Alberto Accomazzi is available from in To post process the xwd output of some of these tools you can use xpr which is part of the Also on several archives are and XtoPS which produce Encapsulated PostScript with trimmings suitable for use in presentations see contrib and contrib Also useful is the PBMPLUS package on many archive servers and the Xim package contains Level color PostScript The XV program can grab a portion of the X display manipulate it and save it in one of the available ImageMagick has similar Also Bristol Technology offers Xprinter an Xlib API for PostScript and PCL printers a demo is on in vendor Bristol ColorSoft offers OPENprint package includes a screen capture facility image processing and support for PostScript and non PostScript Some vendors' implementations of X DECWindows and OpenWindows include session managers or other desktop programs which include print portion of screen or take a snapshot Some platforms also have tools which can be used to grab the frame buffer directly the Sun systems for example have a 'screendump' program which produces a Sun raster Some X terminals have local screen dump utilities to write PostScript to a local serial Some vendors' implementations of lpr Sony include direct support for printing xwd files but you'll typically need some other package to massage the output into a useful format which you can get to the Subject How do I make a color PostScript screendump of the X display If you need color PostScript in particular you can grab the screen image using a program which can produce color PostScript such as xgrabsc and xv grab the screen image using xwd and post process xwd into color You can do this using or the XtoPS program from the ImageMagick The PBMPLUS package is also good for this as is the Xim Subject How do I make a screendump including the X cursor This can't be done unless the X server has been Consider instead a system dependent mechanism for capturing the frame Subject How do I convert view Mac TIFF GIF Sun PICT img FAX images in X The likeliest program is an incarnation of Jef Poskanzer's useful Portable Bitmap Toolkit which includes a number of programs for converting among various image It includes support for many types of bitmaps gray scale images and full color PBMPLUS has been updated recently the most recent version is on export in contrib Another tool is San Diego Supercomputing Center's IMtools 'imconv' in particular which packages the functionality of PBM into a single It's available anonymous ftp from Useful for viewing some image formats is Jim Frost's xloadimage a version of which is in the directory contrib clients xloadimage there are later versions available including contrib on Graeme Gill's updates to an earlier version of xloadimage are also on export see