also includes an ImageViewPort widget and a FileDialog some material from Larry Carroll Subject How can I change the titlebar of my xterm window The solution involves sending an escape sequence to xterm which will cause it to update the property which the window manager relies upon for the string which appears in the window A solution is as easy as typing this in an xterm running a shell echo ESC TEXT G where ESC is the escape key TEXT is the string you wish to have displayed and G is a Control G the BEL character Here is a more complicated csh alias which changes the titlebar to the current working directory when you change directories alias newcd 'cd echo n ESC cwd G' The digit ' ' in these strings indicates to xterm that it should change only the title of the window to change both the title and the name used in the icon use the digit ' ' instead and use ' ' to change only the icon Note another way to do this which prevents an incorrect display of the local directory if a modified cd is used in a subshell is to wrap the escape sequences into the prompt Note on an IBM RS is may be necessary to begin the sequence with a Subject Where can I find the xterm control sequences The best source of such information is in your sources in the file a PostScript version is in mit hardcopy clients O'Reilly's Volume the X User's Guide includes an version of the control sequences the standard volume will be available and a Motif version of the book is available The current guide includes an outdated version of the control Other good sources of information include the version of that document and also the file in the sources called mit clients xterm a compilation put together by Skip Montanaro GE CR D listing the It dates from but is fairly A hardcopy version was published in the December XNextEvent the XUG newsletter In a pinch a manual will last updated Subject Why does the xterm et al fail against the server Subject How can I use characters above ASCII in xterm In order to use s